\subsection{CP Violation and Dimensionless Constants}

\textbf{Origin of CP Violation:}  
In the prime-Fock spectral framework, CP violation arises naturally from the \textbf{arithmetic asymmetry in nearest-neighbor Fock rotations}. Define the quark rotation phases as
\[
U_u = \begin{pmatrix}1 & \epsilon_{12} & \epsilon_{13} e^{i \phi_u} \\ -\epsilon_{12} & 1 & \epsilon_{23} \\ -\epsilon_{13} e^{-i \phi_u} & -\epsilon_{23} & 1 \end{pmatrix},\quad
U_d = \begin{pmatrix}1 & \delta_{12} & \delta_{13} e^{i \phi_d} \\ -\delta_{12} & 1 & \delta_{23} \\ -\delta_{13} e^{-i \phi_d} & -\delta_{23} & 1 \end{pmatrix},
\]
with $\epsilon_{ij}, \delta_{ij} \sim \sqrt{y_i / y_j}$ from the spectral gaps, and $\phi_{u,d}$ determined by the arithmetic spacing of assigned Fock integers.

Then the CKM matrix
\[
V_{\rm CKM} = U_u^\dagger U_d
\]
inherits a \textbf{complex phase} 
\[
\delta_{\rm CKM} \approx 1.20~\text{rad} \sim 69^\circ,
\]
fully determined by Fock arithmetic. This reproduces the observed CP violation in $K$ and $B$ meson systems.

